cd my-docker-app






 Step 3: Create the Required Files
Inside the my-docker-app directory, you need to create three files:

app.js â€“ A simple Node.js script

package.json â€“ Contains metadata and dependencies

Dockerfile â€“ Instructions for building the Docker image

You can use nano, vim, or any editor. Let's go step by step.

ğŸ“„ 3.1 Create app.js
This file will simply print a message.

bash
Copy
Edit
nano app.js
Paste this content inside:

javascript
Copy
Edit
console.log("Hello from Docker!");
Press CTRL + O â†’ Enter to save, then CTRL + X to exit.

ğŸ“„ 3.2 Create package.json
bash
Copy
Edit
nano package.json
Paste the following:

json
Copy
Edit
{
  "name": "docker-app",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "app.js",
  "scripts": {
    "start": "node app.js"
  }
}
Save and exit (CTRL + O, Enter, then CTRL + X).

ğŸ“„ 3.3 Create Dockerfile (no extension)
bash
Copy
Edit
nano Dockerfile
Paste this:

Dockerfile
Copy
Edit
# Use Node.js base image
FROM node:18

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# Copy files
COPY . .

# Install dependencies (none in this case, but good practice)
RUN npm install

# Command to run the app
CMD ["npm", "start"]
Save and exit.

âœ… Step 4: Build the Docker Image
Before this step, make sure Docker is installed and running:

bash
Copy
Edit
docker --version
If Docker is working, build your image:

bash
Copy
Edit
docker build -t my-node-app .
This will:

Download the Node.js base image

Copy your project into the image

Install dependencies (none in this case)

Tag the image as my-node-app

â–¶ï¸ Step 5: Run the Docker Container
Now run your container:

